---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
	{ name: 'Home', url: 'https://victorthuo.com' },
	{ name: 'About', url: 'https://victorthuo.com/about' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
	title="About – Victor Thuo"
	description="Design and strategy leader working at the intersection of product experience, AI, and business outcomes."
	breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
	<!-- Hero Section -->
	<section class="py-20 reveal">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
			<p class="label-arch text-silver-400 mb-4">About</p>
			<h1 class="text-4xl font-display text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-4">
				Victor Thuo
			</h1>
			<p class="text-2xl text-silver-400 font-display" style="font-weight: 300;">
				Experience Design & AI Product Strategy
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Bio Section -->
	<section class="py-16 reveal">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
			<p class="label-arch text-silver-400 mb-4">Background</p>
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-display text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-8">
				Background
			</h2>
			<div class="space-y-6 text-silver-400 font-sans leading-relaxed" style="font-weight: 300;">
				<p>
					I'm a design and strategy leader who works at the intersection of product experience, AI, and business outcomes. I've spent nearly a decade helping organizations design, build, and scale digital products across enterprise technology, healthcare, financial services, and automotive.
				</p>

				<p>
					My path started in product design but evolved as I realized that craft alone doesn't move the needle. The best products succeed because of clear systems thinking, sharp strategy, and obsessive attention to how people experience the work, from first click to full adoption. That's what I focus on: designing the whole arc, not just the interface.
				</p>

				<p>
					I've led the experience design that scaled an AI platform to 7,800 users, built a developer portal that doubled engineering velocity, driven a DTC strategy that unlocked 5X growth, and managed an enterprise migration of 31,000 people with zero critical errors. The pattern across all of it: treat design as a business discipline, stay close to the data, and never stop asking whether the thing you built is actually being used.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Design Philosophy -->
	<section class="py-16 reveal">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
			<p class="label-arch text-silver-400 mb-4">Philosophy</p>
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-display text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-12">
				Design Philosophy
			</h2>
			<div class="space-y-10">
				<div>
					<h3 class="text-xl font-display font-semibold text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-3">
						Design is a business discipline.
					</h3>
					<p class="text-silver-400 font-sans leading-relaxed" style="font-weight: 300;">
						If the product doesn't move a metric, the design didn't work. I tie every decision, from information architecture to interaction patterns, to adoption rates, error reduction, and time to value. Beautiful work that doesn't drive outcomes is a portfolio piece, not a strategy.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<h3 class="text-xl font-display font-semibold text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-3">
						Start with the system, not the screen.
					</h3>
					<p class="text-silver-400 font-sans leading-relaxed" style="font-weight: 300;">
						The best solutions come from understanding how the whole thing fits together: the technology, the people, the organizational dynamics. I think in systems and design in details. That's how you get products that are elegant to use and practical to build.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<h3 class="text-xl font-display font-semibold text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-3">
						Enterprise users deserve great design.
					</h3>
					<p class="text-silver-400 font-sans leading-relaxed" style="font-weight: 300;">
						The person using your internal tool at 3pm just used a consumer app at noon. They know what good feels like. Complexity is real, but it's not an excuse. I design enterprise experiences with the same rigor and craft, because clarity scales and confusion compounds.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- How I Work -->
	<section class="py-16 border-y border-silver-200 dark:border-silver-800 reveal">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
			<p class="label-arch text-silver-400 mb-4">Process</p>
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-display text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-8">
				How I Work
			</h2>
			<div class="space-y-6 text-silver-400 font-sans leading-relaxed" style="font-weight: 300;">
				<p>
					I start by understanding the real problem. Not the one in the brief, but the one that emerges when you talk to the people closest to the work. I spend time with stakeholders, end users, and the engineers who'll build it. That's where the useful information lives.
				</p>

				<p>
					Then I move fast and stay precise. Prototype early, test with real people, measure what matters. I work across product, engineering, and leadership. Not in a handoff, but in the room together. Design decisions are better when they account for technical constraints and business realities from the start.
				</p>

				<p>
					The work doesn't end at launch. I also think through adoption: onboarding, communication, rollout strategy. A product that ships but sits unused is a product that failed. I design for outcomes, not deliverables.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Sectors -->
	<section class="py-16 reveal">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
			<p class="label-arch text-silver-400 mb-4">Industries</p>
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-display text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-8">
				Sectors
			</h2>
			<div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
				{['Business Consulting', 'Healthcare', 'Financial Services & FinTech', 'Automotive', 'Consumer Products', 'Enterprise Technology'].map(
					(sector) => (
						<div class="border-l border-clay pl-4 py-2">
							<p class="text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 font-sans font-medium">{sector}</p>
						</div>
					)
				)}
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Recommendations -->
	<section class="py-16 reveal">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
			<p class="label-arch text-silver-400 mb-4">Testimonials</p>
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-display text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-8">
				What others say
			</h2>
			<div class="space-y-8">
				<blockquote class="border-l border-clay pl-6 py-4">
					<p class="text-lg text-silver-400 font-sans mb-2 italic" style="font-weight: 300;">
						"Victor is a rare design leader who understands business as well as he understands design. He doesn't just design beautiful interfaces, he designs for adoption and impact. Working with him transformed how we think about product strategy."
					</p>
					<p class="text-sm font-sans text-silver-600">
						[Recommendation from LinkedIn]
					</p>
				</blockquote>

				<blockquote class="border-l border-clay pl-6 py-4">
					<p class="text-lg text-silver-400 font-sans mb-2 italic" style="font-weight: 300;">
						"Victor brings a strategic lens to every decision, grounded in behavioral research and business acumen. He's as comfortable facilitating executive alignment as he is diving into detailed interaction design. His work directly moved the needle on our key metrics."
					</p>
					<p class="text-sm font-sans text-silver-600">
						[Recommendation from LinkedIn]
					</p>
				</blockquote>

				<blockquote class="border-l border-clay pl-6 py-4">
					<p class="text-lg text-silver-400 font-sans mb-2 italic" style="font-weight: 300;">
						"Collaborating with Victor was a masterclass in how to think about enterprise UX. He got the complexity, but never let it compromise the experience. His team loved working with him, and our users noticed the difference immediately."
					</p>
					<p class="text-sm font-sans text-silver-600">
						[Recommendation from LinkedIn]
					</p>
				</blockquote>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Connect -->
	<section class="py-20 border-t border-silver-200 dark:border-silver-800 reveal">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
			<p class="label-arch text-silver-400 mb-4">Contact</p>
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-display text-silver-900 dark:text-silver-100 mb-8">
				Have something you're working through?
			</h2>
			<p class="text-silver-400 font-sans mb-6 text-lg" style="font-weight: 300;">
				I'm always interested in hard problems. The kind where good design, clear strategy, and smart execution all have to come together.
			</p>
			<a
				href="https://linkedin.com/in/victorthuo"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noopener noreferrer"
				class="inline-block text-silver-800 dark:text-silver-200 font-sans font-medium border-b-2 border-clay hover:text-clay transition-colors"
			>
				Let's talk on LinkedIn →
			</a>
		</div>
	</section>
</BaseLayout>
